    "details": {
      "en": {
        "id": "en",
        "purpose": "To guide severity classification, risk stratification, diagnostic, and management decisions in adult patients (≥18 years old) with suspected or confirmed SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) infection in the emergency department.",
        "keywords": [
          "ACEP",
          "american",
          "college",
          "emergency",
          "physicians",
          "emergency department",
          "COVID-19",
          "SARS-CoV-2",
          "NIH criteria",
          "PRIEST score",
          "risk",
          "factors",
          "severity",
          "classification",
          "management",
          "tool"
        ],
        "use": "Use to guide severity classification, risk stratification, diagnostic, and management decisions in adult patients (≥18 years old) with suspected or confirmed SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) infection in the emergency department.\n\nfor NIH severity criteria refer to: https://www.covid19treatmentguidelines.nih.gov/overview/clinical-spectrum/.\n\nPRIEST score and additional risk factors are used when the NIH severity score is mild or moderate.\nPRIEST score is used to predicts adverse outcome in adults presenting to ED with suspected COVID-19 and it consists of 10 elements: sex, age, respiratory rate, oxygen saturation, heart rate, systolic BP, temperature, alertness, inspired oxygen and performance status.\n\nCovid-19 risk factors consist of 13 factors which are: cancer, cardiovascular disease, diabetes types II, Downs's syndrome, hypertension, immunosuppression, neurologic disease, obesity, obstructive sleep apnea, pregnancy, renal disease and steroid usage.\n\nthe evidence on this topic is evolving quickly and may change.\n",
        "misuse": "Not to be used a substitute for clinicians' clinical judgement.\n\nNot to be considered as an exhaustive in regards to diagnostic and treatment recommendations for patients with COVID-19 and COVID-like illness. \n\nNot to be used for for patients presenting with symptoms conditions that may be manifestations of COVID-19 and may also be manifestations of other serious disease (e.g. MI, PE, stroke), they will require additional specific diagnostic and therapeutic interventions not discussed in this tool.\n",
        "copyright": "CDS Cambio"
      }
    },
    "other_details": {
      "references": "COVID-19 Treatment Guidelines Panel. Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Treatment Guidelines. National Institutes of Health. Available at https://www.covid19treatmentguidelines.nih.gov/. Accessed [26-08-2021].\n\nEmergency department COVID-19 Management Tool. American College of Emergency Physicians. Available at https://www.acep.org/corona/COVID-19-alert/covid-19-articles/covid-19-ED-management-tool-now-available/. Accessed[26-08-2021].\n\n"
    }
  },
